Django Advanced Retake Exam
Individual Project
Project Requirements for Django Advanced Course @ SoftUni
Your project is an opportunity to demonstrate your understanding of advanced Django concepts and RESTful API development by building a functional, visually appealing, and production-ready web application. You are expected to apply everything you have learned - from designing models, serializers, and class-based views to creating dynamic templates and maintaining clean, modular code. The project should showcase your ability to design, implement, and deploy a real-world solution independently, following Django's best practices and conventions. Focus on building a cohesive, original concept that reflects both technical proficiency and thoughtful architectural design.
    1. Project Requirements
Important Notes:
    • The submitted project must be downloadable, installable, and runnable without modifications. After installing dependencies and applying migrations, the application should start successfully using the default configuration.
    • All environment variables and credentials required for local testing must be clearly documented in your README file.

Core Functional Requirements
    • Your application must include both a public section (accessible to anonymous users) and a private section (accessible only to authenticated users).
        ◦ The application must support user registration, login, and logout functionality.
    • There must be at least two user groups defined in the admin site, each with distinct permissions.
    • The built-in Django User model must be extended.
Technical Stack
    • The application must be implemented using Django and/or Django REST Framework (latest stable versions).
        ◦ Your project must consist of at least five (5) Django apps, each with clearly defined responsibilities.
        ◦ The application must define at least five (5) database models.
            ▪ Models created via inheritance or one-to-one relationships count as one model (e.g., User <-> Profile).
            ▪ Your database architecture must include at least two many-to-one and two many-to-many relationships.
Forms and Validations
    • The application must include at least nine (9) forms with proper data validations.
        ◦ Display user-friendly error messages for invalid input.
        ◦ Implement validations in both models and forms, where appropriate.
        ◦ Customize error messages, help texts, labels, and placeholders.
        ◦ Include read-only or disabled fields in at least two forms.
        ◦ Exclude unnecessary fields when rendering forms.
        ◦ Provide a confirmation step before deleting any object.
Views and APIs
    • Implement views to handle business logic:
        ◦ Use Class-Based Views (CBVs) as the main approach (approximately 90% CBVs).
        ◦ Handle forms correctly (GET and POST methods, validation, saving).
        ◦ Use redirects after successful create/update actions.
        ◦ Implement at least two RESTful API endpoints or services using Django REST Framework.
            ▪ Use serializers, API views, and permissions appropriately.
Templates and Frontend
    • The application must include at least seventeen (17) web pages/templates built using the Django Template Engine or rendered by a front-end framework (React, Angular, etc.):
        ◦ At least twelve (12) of them must display dynamic data from the database.
        ◦ Implement full CRUD functionality for at least three (3) models (manageable by owners).
        ◦ Include pages that display all objects, filtered/sorted objects, single-object details, user details, or profiles, etc.
        ◦ Showcase built-in and custom template filters/tags.
        ◦ Provide custom error pages (404, 500, etc.).
        ◦ Use a base template (not included in the 15-count).
        ◦ Apply template inheritance and reusable partial templates.
        ◦ Ensure that navigation links connect all pages consistently, and every page includes a footer.
        ◦ Display or hide links appropriately for anonymous/authenticated users.
        ◦ Templates can be reused across different views when appropriate.
        ◦ Implement a responsive web design using Bootstrap, an AI-generated layout, or a custom design.
    • All pages in the application must be accessible through navigation links.
        ◦ Avoid "orphan" pages that can only be reached by typing a URL manually.
        ◦ Ensure consistent navigation menus and footers across the site.
        ◦ Failure to provide functional navigation will affect your score, as any inaccessible pages will not be counted or evaluated.
Additional Technical Requirements
    • Implement asynchronous task processing (e.g., Celery, RQ, or asyncio-based tasks).
    • Ensure application security and data protection:
        ◦ Prevent SQL injection, XSS, CSRF, and parameter tampering.
        ◦ Use environment variables for sensitive data (no hardcoded secrets).
    • Use a PostgreSQL or another relational Database System.
    • Store and serve media and static files properly.
    • Include tests for custom logic, views, and user-related functionality (minimum 20 tests).
    • Deploy the project on a cloud-based platform.
        ◦ The functionality and overall behaviour of your project will be assessed primarily based on the deployed version.
        ◦ Ensure that the deployed application is fully functional, synchronized with your GitHub repository, and accessible during the evaluation period.
    • Use GitHub as your version control platform.
        ◦ Submit a public GitHub repository link.
        ◦ There must be a minimum of 9 (nine) commits on 9 (nine) separate days.
Documentation and Code Quality
    • Provide clear project documentation:
        ◦ A comprehensive GitHub README describing setup, dependencies, and deployment.
        ◦ Include environment setup instructions and sample .env configuration.
    • Follow OOP and clean code principles:
        ◦ Apply data encapsulation and proper exception handling.
        ◦ Demonstrate inheritance, abstraction, and polymorphism where relevant.
        ◦ Follow strong cohesion and loose coupling principles.
        ◦ Maintain readable, well-formatted code with clear naming conventions.
Disclaimer
    • It is NOT permissible to use any of the following in your project:
        ◦ Ideas, Models, HTML, CSS, or entire Django apps taken from workshops, exercises, or lectures/presentations.
        ◦ HTML/CSS/JS from JS modules, or any other SoftUni-related courses.
        ◦ AI-generated code (except for HTML/CSS layouts or documentation).
    • If your project is found to be over 60% AI-generated, it will be disqualified (0 points).
    • Focus on developing a unique and original concept that reflects your understanding.
        ◦ Failure to do so will negatively affect your final grade.
    2. Submission Deadline
    • You must submit a GitHub repository link before 15:59 on 21 April 2026 using the submission button in the Retake Exam section, available from 17 April 2026.
    • You may continue improving your project after assessment (after 30 April 2026)
        ◦ Do not push new commits until evaluation is complete; work locally until then.
    • Projects not submitted by the deadline will NOT be evaluated.
    • The assessment is performed manually and typically takes up to 10 days.
    3. Assessment Criteria
    • Originality and Concept (unique idea, relevance, creativity) - maximum 10 points
    • Database Design and Relationships (model structure, M2M, FKs, constraints, fields, methods, Meta, query usage) - maximum 5 points
    • User Model extension, Groups/Permissions, Authentication - maximum 5 points
    • Forms, Validation, Media files handling - maximum 5 points
    • Views Implementation (90% CBVs, mixins, advanced techniques) - maximum 10 points
    • Pages (design, navigation, dynamic data) - maximum 10 points
    • Asynchronous Processing (task queues, scheduling, background jobs)- maximum 10 points
    • RESTful APIs (serializers, permissions, integration) - maximum 10 points
    • Deployment and Environment Configuration - maximum 10 points
    • Tests (coverage, correctness, relevance, minimum 20 tests) - maximum 5 points
    • Security and Data protection, Advanced Features and Functionality (not demonstrated by lecturer) - maximum 10 points
    • Project Documentation (README clarity, setup instructions, structure overview) - maximum 4 points
    • Version Control (Git discipline: commits, structure, descriptive messages) - maximum 3 points
    • Code Quality and Architecture (readability, OOP, structure) - maximum 3 points